{"title_page": "Robert Rippberger", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Robert Rippberger\n| image              = Robert Rippberger Headshot.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1988|9|7}}\n| birth_place        = [[Boulder, Colorado]]\n| nationality        = [[United States|American]]\n| education          = [[University of California, Berkeley]]\n| occupation         = [[Film director]], [[film producer]], and [[screenwriter]]\n| years_active       = 2006\u2013present\n| website            = {{url|http://robertrippberger.com}}\n}}\n'''Robert Rippberger''' (born September 7, 1988) is an American [[film director]] and [[film producer]]. He is the director/producer of ''[[Strive (film)|Strive]]'' with [[Danny Glover]] and the Hulu released documentary [[7 Days in Syria]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Collinson|first1=Gary|title=Danny Glover joins Harlem drama Strive|url=https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2018/06/danny-glover-joins-harlem-drama-strive/|website=FlickeringMyth}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=di Giovanni|first1=Janine|title=REPORTER DOCUMENTS LIFE IN ALEPPO IN '7 DAYS IN SYRIA'|url=http://www.newsweek.com/life-aleppo-7-days-syria-491850|website=Newsweek|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> Robert executive produced with [[Jason Blum]] the feature documentary [[Alive and Kicking (2016 film)|Alive and Kicking]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=DeFore|first1=John|title='Alive and Kicking': SXSW Review|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/alive-kicking-sxsw-review-872967|website=Hollywood Reporter}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lang|first1=Brett|title=Blumhouse Boards Swing Dance Documentary \u2018Alive and Kicking\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/blumhouse-alive-and-kicking-1201689861/|website=Variety}}</ref> The film was sold to [[Magnolia Pictures]] and [[Netflix]] after its debut at the 2016 [[SXSW Film Festival]], where it received a Grand Jury nomination.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lincoln|first1=Ross|title=Magnolia Picks Up Blumhouse SXSW Docu \u2018Alive And Kicking\u2019|url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/blumhouse-swing-dance-docu-alive-and-kicking-acquired-by-magnolia-1201739343/|website=Deadline}}</ref>\n\n== Narrative Work ==\nRippberger is the director of the 2019 drama ''[[Strive (film)|Strive]]'', about a girl from the projects in Harlem who works to attend Yale.<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Robert Rippberger and She Rises Smith About Their Upcoming Movie Strive|url=https://markmeets.com/celeb-interviews/interview-with-robert-rippberger-and-sha-risse-smith-about-their-upcoming-movie-strive/|website=MarkMeets}}</ref> Inspired by true stories, Strive stars Grammy-nominated JoiStaRR, Shaylin Becton, Ricky Flowers Jr, Chelsea Lee Williams, and Emmy-nominated Danny Glover, with music composed by Grammy-winning producer [[Warryn Campbell]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Joi Campbell|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/joi-campbell|website=Grammy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Judah Bellamy and Shaylin Becton Join The Lion King|url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/155828/judah-bellamy-and-shaylin-becton-join-the-lion-king/|website=Broadway}}</ref>\n\nRippberger is currently in pre-production as the producer of ''The Inventor'', a stop-motion feature film written and directed by Jim Capobianco, the Oscar-nominated writer of Pixar's [[Ratatouille]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Carr|first1=Martin|title=Exclusive Interview \u2013 Jim Capobianco on Disney, Pixar and his new film The Inventor|url=https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2018/05/exclusive-interview-jim-capobianco-on-disney-pixar-and-his-new-film-the-inventor/|website=FlickeringMyth}}</ref>\n\n== Documentary ==\nIn 2016, Rippberger's feature documentary 7 Days in Syria, which follows journalist Janine di Giovanni's 2012 trip to Aleppo, was screened at Britain's [[House of Lords]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\"7 Days in Syria\" screening in British Parliament; House of Lords|url=https://ahtribune.com/world/north-africa-south-west-asia/syria-crisis/416-7-days-in-syria-house-of-lords.html|website=AH Tribune}}</ref> The film has played in over 50 cities worldwide, on television in Denmark, Sweden, and China, and via streaming service [[Hulu]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.standard.net/Local/2017/03/28/Documentary-film-7-Days-in-Syria-showing-for-free-Wednesday-in-Ogden|title=Documentary film '7 Days in Syria' showing for free Wednesday in Ogden|last=Standard-Examiner|work=Standard-Examiner|access-date=2017-07-05}}</ref> The documentary is currently available via Amazon Prime and other VOD providers. The film was well received by critics and personally championed by United Nations Special Envoy [[Angelina Jolie]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gorman|first1=Michele|title=WATCH: TRAILER FOR '7 DAYS IN SYRIA,' A DOCUMENTARY ABOUT REPORTING ON WAR|url=https://www.newsweek.com/trailer-7-days-syria-janine-di-giovanni-396683|website=Newsweek}}</ref>\n\nRippberger went on to executive produce Alive and Kicking, a documentary about [[swing dancing]], which premiered at the 2016 [[SXSW Film Festival]] to a Grand Jury nomination, and was released in 2017 by [[Magnolia Pictures]]. Alive and Kicking was named the film to watch by [[The New York Times]] watching section, received a 100% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], and was invited to be part of the 2018/19 American Film Showcase, the State Department's diplomacy through cinema program.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Castillo|first1=Monica|title=Alive and Kicking|url=https://www.nytimes.com/watching/titles/alive-and-kicking|website=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Alive and Kicking|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/alive_and_kicking_2017|website=Rotten Tomatoes}}</ref> The film is currently available on Netflix.\n\nIn 2011, Rippberger co-created a seven part documentary series published by [[The New York Times]] interviewing politicians and world leaders regarding the world's biggest crises.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Krupp|first1=Tyler|title=An Interview with Gideon Rosen|url=https://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/author/tyler-krupp/|website=The New York Times}}</ref> He was the 2012 recipient of the Dan Eldon Activist Award for producing and directing ''A Ride With Matt'', later retitled ''Breaking the Cycle'', a documentary feature about Huntington's Disease. The award is given to filmmakers for best use of media to effect positive change.<ref>{{cite web|title=Documentary On Huntington's Wins The Dan Eldon Activist Award At The 8th Annual MY HERO International Film Festival|url=https://myhero.com/EldonAward2012}}</ref>\n\nRippberger is the previous president of I Imagine, a socially conscious technology and media organization which runs the annual I Imagine Film Festival and conference. He is also the co-founder and editor of the magazine and podcast Cinema of Change, whose mission is to create a central, continuously relevant source of accessible information on social impact filmmaking.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mission Statement|url=http://www.cinemaofchange.com/about-the-magazine/mission-statement/}}</ref>\n\n== Music Videos ==\nIn 2014, Rippberger directed the music video [[Ab Laut Aa]] by EDM DJ [[Sanjoy]] featuring [[Sunidhi Chauhan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Check out Sunidhi Chauhan\u2019s Single \u2018AB LAUT AA\u2019|url=https://bollyspice.com/check-out-sunidhi-chauhans-single-ab-laut-aa/|website=BollySpice.com}}</ref> The video has 1.5 million views on YouTube and won Best Music Video that year at the [[VIMA Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanjoy ft. Sunidhi Chauhan - Ab Laut Aa - Official Music Video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X9XT-o1QpD0|website=YouTube.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\"VIMA India 2014 Winners List\" |url=https://globalvima.com/ |website=Bite My Music |accessdate=16 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nThirty years after the song's initial release, in 2018 Rippberger directed the official music video for \u201cSuicide\u201d by [[Busy Bee Starski]], the single off his gold album Running Thangs. Originating from New York City, [[Hip Hop Hall of Fame]] inductee [[Busy Bee Starski]] is considered one of the founders of modern hip-hop, and the star of the 1983 film [[Wild Style]], billed as the first hip-hop motion picture.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gonzales|first1=David|title=\u2018Wild Style\u2019 at 25: A Film That Envisioned the Future of Hip-Hop Culture|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/12/nyregion/12wild.html?mtrref=www.google.com}}</ref> The music video guest stars rapper [[Ice-T]].\n\n== Writing ==\nIn 2014, Rippberger published a novel with Regent Press called Escape to Anywhere Else with a foreword by [[Mariel Hemingway]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Escape to Anywhere Else|url=https://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/escape-to-anywhere-else-robert-rippberger/1118954936?ean=9781587902680|website=Barnes and Noble}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gandleman|first1=Joe|title=BOOK REVIEW: Escape to Anywhere Else by Robert Rippberger|url=https://themoderatevoice.com/book-review-escape-anywhere-else-robert-rippberger/}}</ref> Robert is the co-founder and co-editor of the magazine, [[Cinema of Change]], along with Tobias Deml. He is a contributing writer to [[The Huffington Post]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Team|url=http://www.cinemaofchange.com/about-the-magazine/team/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Robert Rippberger|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/author/robert-rippberger|website=HuffPost}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nRippberger began filmmaking at age 13. As a freshman in high school, he enrolled in filmmaking classes at the [[University of Colorado Boulder]], studied under directing teacher Judith Weston, and at [[UCLA]] Film School in Los Angeles. In 2005, at age 16, he made his first feature film, \"The Hoodwink.\"\n\nRippberger received a B.A. in [[philosophy]] from the [[University of California, Berkeley]] in 2010, where he was awarded in 2009 the Roselyn Schneider Eisner Prize for his film \"In the Middle.\" It is considered the highest achievement in creativity given on the UC, Berkeley campus.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prizes and Honors / Roselyn Schneider Eisner Prizes in Film and Video|url=http://financialaid.berkeley.edu/prizes-and-honors-roselyn-schneider-eisner-prizes-film-and-video|website=Berkeley.edu}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Rippberger founded Aletheia Films, named after [[Aletheia]] (a philosophical concept in philosophy reflecting a disclosing of truth) with a view to make entertaining and impactful films for mass audiences. The company produces feature films, series, documentaries, commercials, music videos, and major events.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Liz|title=Robert Rippberger chats Aletheia Films|url=https://newsblaze.com/entertainment/interviews/robert-rippberger-chats-aletheia-films_130927/|website=Newsblaze}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Features===\n*''The Hoodwink'' (2006)\n*''Visions for the Future'' (2013)\n*''Breaking the Cycle'' (2013)\n*''Face of Unity: Nelson Mandela'' (2014)\n*''[[7 Days in Syria]]'' (2015)\n*''[[Alive and Kicking (2016 film)|Alive and Kicking]]'' (2016) (executive producer)<ref>{{cite web|title=Robert Rippberger|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3163495|website=The Internet Movie Database}}</ref>\n*''[[Strive (film)|Strive]]'' (2019)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://filmpulse.net/kickstart-sunday-strivers-row/|title=Kickstart Sunday: STRIVER'S ROW {{!}} Film Pulse|date=2017-04-23|work=Film Pulse|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en-US}}</ref>\n*''Public Enemy Number One'' (2020)\n\n===Shorts===\n*\"Grave\" (2004)\n*\"R.I.P.\" (2005)\n*\"In the Middle\" (2009)\n*\"Noor (2011)\" (co-director)\n*\"Haven (2011)\"\n*\"ThinkingAloud\" (2011)\n*\"A Night at the Office\" (2012) (co-producer)\n\n===Music videos===\n*\"[[Ab Laut Aa]]\" by [[Sanjoy]] featuring [[Sunidhi Chauhan]] (2013)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Port 22|title=Sanjoy ft. Sunidhi Chauhan - Ab Laut Aa - Official Music Video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X9XT-o1QpD0|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n*\"Set Me Free\" by [[Sanjoy]] (2014)<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanjoy - Set Me Free|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=coeo98XmDdE|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n*\"Suicide\" by [[Busy Bee Starski]] (2018)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Port 22|title=Busy Bee - Suicide - Official Music Video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DrLPVsHeu4Q|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"|Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"|Award\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"|Nominated Work\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"|Category\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"|Role\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"|Result\n|-\n|2011\n|The Eisner Prize\n|In the Middle\n|Highest Achievement in Creativity\n|Director/Producer\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Prizes and Honors / Roselyn Schneider Eisner Prizes in Film and Video|url=http://financialaid.berkeley.edu/prizes-and-honors-roselyn-schneider-eisner-prizes-film-and-video|website=Berkeley.edu}}</ref>\n|-\n|2012\n|Dan Eldon Activist Award\n|Breaking the Cycle\n|Activist Filmmaker Award\n|Director/Producer\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Documentary On Huntington's Wins The Dan Eldon Activist Award At The 8th Annual MY HERO International Film Festival|url=https://myhero.com/EldonAward2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|2015\n|[[Fingal Film Festival]]\n|[[7 Days in Syria]]\n|Outstanding Achievement in Media\n|Director/Producer\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=fffintern |title=Fingal Film Festival Winners Announced |url=http://www.fingalfilmfest.com/author/fffintern/ |website=Fingal Film Festival}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|Amsterdam Lift-Off Festival\n|[[7 Days in Syria]]\n|Jury Selection Best Feature\n|Director/Producer\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web |title=The Lift-Off Season Awards |url=https://liftoff.network/lift-off-season-awards/ |website=Lift-Off Network}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|[[SXSW Film Festival]]\n|[[Alive and Kicking (2016 film)|Alive and Kicking]]\n|Grand Jury Award\n|Executive Producer\n|{{nom}}<ref>{{cite web |title=The 9th Annual Frankfort Film Festival |url=https://www.visitbenzie.com/9th-annual-frankfort-film-festival-takes-place-october-19-22-featuring-19-international-award-winning-films/ |website=Visit Benzie |accessdate=10 October 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|2017\n|Palm Springs Film Festival\n|[[Alive and Kicking (2016 film)|Alive and Kicking]]\n|Best of Fest\n|Executive Producer\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web |title=THAT\u2019S A WRAP: PSIFF Awards and \"Best of Fest\" Winners |url=http://coachellavalleyweekly.com/thats-a-wrap-psiff-awards-and-best-of-fest-winners/ |website=Coachella Valley Weekly}}</ref>\n|-\n|2019\n|Harlem International Film Festival\n|[[Strive (film)|Strive]]\n|Audience Award\n|Director/Producer\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Harlem International Film Festival: 2019 Awards |url=http://harlemfilmfestival.org/2019-awards/}}</ref>\n|-\n|2019\n|American Black Film Festival\n|[[Strive (film)|Strive]]\n|Audience Award\n|Director/Producer\n|{{nom}}<ref>{{cite web |title=American Black Film Festival (ABFF) 2019 Awards Winners |url=https://www.blackfilm.com/read/2019/06/american-black-film-festival-abff-2019-awards-winners/}}</ref>\n|-\n|2019\n|American Black Film Festival\n|[[Strive (film)|Strive]]\n|Best Screenplay\n|Director/Producer\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web |title=American Black Film Festival (ABFF) 2019 Awards Winners |url=https://www.blackfilm.com/read/2019/06/american-black-film-festival-abff-2019-awards-winners/}}</ref>\n|-\n|2019\n|The Valley Film Festival\n|[[Strive (film)|Strive]]\n|Best Narrative Feature\n|Director/Producer\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Audience and Juried Award Winners: |url=http://www.valleyfilmfest.com/valleyfilmfest/app/home |website=The Valley Film Festival |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2019\n|Awareness Film Festival\n|[[Strive (film)|Strive]]\n|Audience Award\n|Director/Producer\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Awards |url=https://www.awarenessfestival.org/awards/ |website=Awareness Film Festival |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2019\n|DOCLA\n|Public Enemy Number One\n|Storyteller and Producing Award\n|Director/Producer\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web |title=2019 Awards |url=https://www.docla.org/2019awards |website=DOCLA.org |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2020\n|New Jersey Film Festival\n|[[Strive (film)|Strive]]\n|Best Feature Film\n|Director/Producer\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web |title=New Jersey Film Festival Spring 2020 Winners Announced! |url=https://www.newjerseystage.com/articles/2020/02/17/new-jersey-film-festival-spring-2020-winners-announced/ |website=newjerseystage.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|nm3163495}}\n* [http://www.robertrippberger.com/ Robert Rippberger website]\n* [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/robert-rippberger/ The Huffington Post]\n* [http://www.7daysinsyriafilm.com/ ''7 Days in Syria'' documentary film website]\n* [http://www.cinemaofchange.com/ Cinema of Change website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rippberger, Robert}}\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:American film producers]]\n[[Category:American music video directors]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American documentary filmmakers]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Colorado]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Boulder, Colorado]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Colorado]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Robert Rippberger\n| image              = Robert Rippberger Headshot.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1988|9|7}}\n| birth_place        = [[Boulder, Colorado]]\n| nationality        = [[United States|American]]\n| education          = [[University of California, Berkeley]]\n| occupation         = [[Film director]], [[film producer]], and [[screenwriter]]\n| years_active       = 2006\u2013present\n| website            = {{url|http://robertrippberger.com}}\n}}\n'''Robert Rippberger''' (born September 7, 1988) is an American [[film director]] and [[film producer]]. He is the director/producer of ''[[Strive (film)|Strive]]'' with [[Danny Glover]] and the Hulu released documentary [[7 Days in Syria]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Collinson|first1=Gary|title=Danny Glover joins Harlem drama Strive|url=https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2018/06/danny-glover-joins-harlem-drama-strive/|website=FlickeringMyth}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=di Giovanni|first1=Janine|title=REPORTER DOCUMENTS LIFE IN ALEPPO IN '7 DAYS IN SYRIA'|url=http://www.newsweek.com/life-aleppo-7-days-syria-491850|website=Newsweek|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> Robert executive produced with [[Jason Blum]] the feature documentary [[Alive and Kicking (2016 film)|Alive and Kicking]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=DeFore|first1=John|title='Alive and Kicking': SXSW Review|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/alive-kicking-sxsw-review-872967|website=Hollywood Reporter}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lang|first1=Brett|title=Blumhouse Boards Swing Dance Documentary \u2018Alive and Kicking\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/blumhouse-alive-and-kicking-1201689861/|website=Variety}}</ref> The film was sold to [[Magnolia Pictures]] and [[Netflix]] after its debut at the 2016 [[SXSW Film Festival]], where it received a Grand Jury nomination.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lincoln|first1=Ross|title=Magnolia Picks Up Blumhouse SXSW Docu \u2018Alive And Kicking\u2019|url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/blumhouse-swing-dance-docu-alive-and-kicking-acquired-by-magnolia-1201739343/|website=Deadline}}</ref>\n\n== Narrative Work ==\nRippberger is the director of the 2019 drama ''[[Strive (film)|Strive]]'', about a girl from the projects in Harlem who works to attend Yale.<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Robert Rippberger and She Rises Smith About Their Upcoming Movie Strive|url=https://markmeets.com/celeb-interviews/interview-with-robert-rippberger-and-sha-risse-smith-about-their-upcoming-movie-strive/|website=MarkMeets}}</ref> Inspired by true stories, Strive stars Grammy-nominated JoiStaRR, Shaylin Becton, Ricky Flowers Jr, Chelsea Lee Williams, and Emmy-nominated Danny Glover, with music composed by Grammy-winning producer [[Warryn Campbell]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Joi Campbell|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/joi-campbell|website=Grammy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Judah Bellamy and Shaylin Becton Join The Lion King|url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/155828/judah-bellamy-and-shaylin-becton-join-the-lion-king/|website=Broadway}}</ref>\n\nRippberger is currently in pre-production as the producer of ''The Inventor'', a stop-motion feature film written and directed by Jim Capobianco, the Oscar-nominated writer of Pixar\u2019s [[Ratatouille]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Carr|first1=Martin|title=Exclusive Interview \u2013 Jim Capobianco on Disney, Pixar and his new film The Inventor|url=https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2018/05/exclusive-interview-jim-capobianco-on-disney-pixar-and-his-new-film-the-inventor/|website=FlickeringMyth}}</ref>\n\n== Documentary ==\nIn 2016, Rippberger\u2019s feature documentary [[7 Days in Syria]], which follows journalist Janine di Giovanni\u2019s 2012 trip to Aleppo, was screened at Britain\u2019s [[House of Lords]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\"7 Days in Syria\" screening in British Parliament; House of Lords|url=https://ahtribune.com/world/north-africa-south-west-asia/syria-crisis/416-7-days-in-syria-house-of-lords.html|website=AH Tribune}}</ref> The film has played in over 50 cities worldwide, on television in Denmark, Sweden, and China, and via streaming service [[Hulu]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.standard.net/Local/2017/03/28/Documentary-film-7-Days-in-Syria-showing-for-free-Wednesday-in-Ogden|title=Documentary film '7 Days in Syria' showing for free Wednesday in Ogden|last=Standard-Examiner|work=Standard-Examiner|access-date=2017-07-05}}</ref> The documentary is currently available via Amazon Prime and other VOD providers. The film was well received by critics and personally championed by United Nations Special Envoy [[Angelina Jolie]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gorman|first1=Michele|title=WATCH: TRAILER FOR '7 DAYS IN SYRIA,' A DOCUMENTARY ABOUT REPORTING ON WAR|url=https://www.newsweek.com/trailer-7-days-syria-janine-di-giovanni-396683|website=Newsweek}}</ref>\n\nRippberger went on to executive produce [[Alive and Kicking (2016 film)|Alive and Kicking]], a documentary about [[swing dancing]], which premiered at the 2016 [[SXSW Film Festival]] to a Grand Jury nomination, and was released in 2017 by [[Magnolia Pictures]]. [[Alive and Kicking (2016 film)|Alive and Kicking]] was named the film to watch by [[The New York Times]] watching section, received a 100% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], and was invited to be part of the 2018/19 American Film Showcase, the State Department\u2019s diplomacy through cinema program.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Castillo|first1=Monica|title=Alive and Kicking|url=https://www.nytimes.com/watching/titles/alive-and-kicking|website=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Alive and Kicking|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/alive_and_kicking_2017|website=Rotten Tomatoes}}</ref> The film is currently available on Netflix.\n\nIn 2011, Rippberger co-created a seven part documentary series published by [[The New York Times]] interviewing politicians and world leaders regarding the world\u2019s biggest crises.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Krupp|first1=Tyler|title=An Interview with Gideon Rosen|url=https://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/author/tyler-krupp/|website=The New York Times}}</ref> He was the 2012 recipient of the Dan Eldon Activist Award for producing and directing ''A Ride With Matt'', later retitled ''Breaking the Cycle'', a documentary feature about Huntington\u2019s Disease. The award is given to filmmakers for best use of media to effect positive change.<ref>{{cite web|title=Documentary On Huntington's Wins The Dan Eldon Activist Award At The 8th Annual MY HERO International Film Festival|url=https://myhero.com/EldonAward2012}}</ref>\n\nRippberger is the previous president of I Imagine, a socially conscious technology and media organization which runs the annual I Imagine Film Festival and conference. He is also the co-founder and editor of the magazine and podcast Cinema of Change, whose mission is to create a central, continuously relevant source of accessible information on social impact filmmaking.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mission Statement|url=http://www.cinemaofchange.com/about-the-magazine/mission-statement/}}</ref>\n\n== Music Videos ==\nIn 2014, Rippberger directed the music video [[Ab Laut Aa]] by EDM DJ [[Sanjoy]] featuring [[Sunidhi Chauhan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Check out Sunidhi Chauhan\u2019s Single \u2018AB LAUT AA\u2019|url=https://bollyspice.com/check-out-sunidhi-chauhans-single-ab-laut-aa/|website=BollySpice.com}}</ref> The video has 1.5 million views on YouTube and won Best Music Video that year at the [[VIMA Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanjoy ft. Sunidhi Chauhan - Ab Laut Aa - Official Music Video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X9XT-o1QpD0|website=YouTube.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\"VIMA India 2014 Winners List\" |url=https://globalvima.com/ |website=Bite My Music |accessdate=16 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nThirty years after the song\u2019s initial release, in 2018 Rippberger directed the official music video for \u201cSuicide\u201d by [[Busy Bee Starski]], the single off his gold album Running Thangs. Originating from New York City, [[Hip Hop Hall of Fame]] inductee [[Busy Bee Starski]] is considered one of the founders of modern hip-hop, and the star of the 1983 film [[Wild Style]], billed as the first hip-hop motion picture.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gonzales|first1=David|title=\u2018Wild Style\u2019 at 25: A Film That Envisioned the Future of Hip-Hop Culture|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/12/nyregion/12wild.html?mtrref=www.google.com}}</ref> The music video guest stars rapper [[Ice-T]].\n\n== Writing ==\nIn 2014, Rippberger published a novel with Regent Press called Escape to Anywhere Else with a foreword by [[Mariel Hemingway]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Escape to Anywhere Else|url=https://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/escape-to-anywhere-else-robert-rippberger/1118954936?ean=9781587902680|website=Barnes and Noble}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gandleman|first1=Joe|title=BOOK REVIEW: Escape to Anywhere Else by Robert Rippberger|url=https://themoderatevoice.com/book-review-escape-anywhere-else-robert-rippberger/}}</ref> Robert is the co-founder and co-editor of the magazine, [[Cinema of Change]], along with Tobias Deml. He is a contributing writer to [[The Huffington Post]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Team|url=http://www.cinemaofchange.com/about-the-magazine/team/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Robert Rippberger|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/author/robert-rippberger|website=HuffPost}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nRippberger began filmmaking at age 13. As a freshman in high school, he enrolled in filmmaking classes at the [[University of Colorado Boulder]], studied under directing teacher Judith Weston, and at [[UCLA]] Film School in Los Angeles. In 2005, at age 16, he made his first feature film, \"The Hoodwink.\"\n\nRippberger received a B.A. in [[philosophy]] from the [[University of California, Berkeley]] in 2010, where he was awarded in 2009 the Roselyn Schneider Eisner Prize for his film \"In the Middle.\" It is considered the highest achievement in creativity given on the UC, Berkeley campus.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prizes and Honors / Roselyn Schneider Eisner Prizes in Film and Video|url=http://financialaid.berkeley.edu/prizes-and-honors-roselyn-schneider-eisner-prizes-film-and-video|website=Berkeley.edu}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Rippberger founded Aletheia Films, named after [[Aletheia]] (a philosophical concept in philosophy reflecting a disclosing of truth) with a view to make entertaining and impactful films for mass audiences. The company produces feature films, series, documentaries, commercials, music videos, and major events.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Liz|title=Robert Rippberger chats Aletheia Films|url=https://newsblaze.com/entertainment/interviews/robert-rippberger-chats-aletheia-films_130927/|website=Newsblaze}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Features===\n*''The Hoodwink'' (2006)\n*''Visions for the Future'' (2013)\n*''Breaking the Cycle'' (2013)\n*''Face of Unity: Nelson Mandela'' (2014)\n*''[[7 Days in Syria]]'' (2015)\n*''[[Alive and Kicking (2016 film)|Alive and Kicking]]'' (2016) (executive producer)<ref>{{cite web|title=Robert Rippberger|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3163495|website=The Internet Movie Database}}</ref>\n*''[[Strive (film)|Strive]]'' (2019)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://filmpulse.net/kickstart-sunday-strivers-row/|title=Kickstart Sunday: STRIVER'S ROW {{!}} Film Pulse|date=2017-04-23|work=Film Pulse|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en-US}}</ref>\n*''Public Enemy Number One'' (2020)\n\n===Shorts===\n*\"Grave\" (2004)\n*\"R.I.P.\" (2005)\n*\"In the Middle\" (2009)\n*\"Noor (2011)\" (co-director)\n*\"Haven (2011)\"\n*\"ThinkingAloud\" (2011)\n*\"A Night at the Office\" (2012) (co-producer)\n\n===Music videos===\n*\"[[Ab Laut Aa]]\" by [[Sanjoy]] featuring [[Sunidhi Chauhan]] (2013)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Port 22|title=Sanjoy ft. Sunidhi Chauhan - Ab Laut Aa - Official Music Video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X9XT-o1QpD0|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n*\"Set Me Free\" by [[Sanjoy]] (2014)<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanjoy - Set Me Free|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=coeo98XmDdE|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n*\"Suicide\" by [[Busy Bee Starski]] (2018)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Port 22|title=Busy Bee - Suicide - Official Music Video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DrLPVsHeu4Q|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n