eer statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|FA Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]]\n|[[1899\u20131900 Stoke F.C. season|1899\u20131900]]<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|2||0||0||0||2||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career Total\n!2!!0!!0!!0!!2!!0\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roberts, Arthur}}\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Stoke City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:1876 births]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Association football inside forwards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Newcastle-under-Lyme]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthur_Roberts_(footballer,_born_1876)"}
{"title_page": "Jackie Johnson (athlete)", "text_new": "{{short description|American heptathlete}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor = lightblue\n| name           = Jackie Johnson\n| image          = \n| imagesize      = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = Jacquelyn Kate Johnson\n| nickname       = \n| nationality    = {{USA}}\n| residence      = [[Tempe, Arizona]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1984|9|8|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[San Jose, California]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = {{height|m=1.73|abbr=on}}\n| weight         = {{convert|62|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| website        = \n| country        = \n| sport          = [[Athletics (sport)|Athletics]]\n| event          = [[Heptathlon]]\n| collegeteam    = \n| club           =\n| team           = [[Arizona State Sun Devils]]<ref name=usatf/> \n| turnedpro      = \n| coach          = [[Dan O'Brien]]<ref name=usatf/>\n| retired        = \n| coaching       = \n| worlds         = \n| regionals      = \n| nationals      = \n| olympics       = \n| paralympics    = \n| highestranking = \n| pb             = '''Heptathlon''': 6,347 points (2008)\n| medaltemplates = \n}}\n\n'''Jacquelyn Kate \"Jackie\" Johnson''' (born September 8, 1984 in [[San Jose, California]]) is an American heptathlete.<ref>{{cite sports-reference|Jackie Johnson|https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/jo/jackie-johnson-1.html|7 January 2013}}</ref> She is a four-time NCAA outdoor champion (2004, 2006\u20132008), and a three-time NCAA indoor champion (2006\u20132008) while competing for [[Arizona State Sun Devils|Arizona State University]]. She also set a personal best of 6,347 points by placing second at the 2008 U.S. Olympic Trials in [[Eugene, Oregon]], which guaranteed her a qualifying place for the Olympics.<ref>{{cite news|title=Johnson Places Second in Heptathlon to Earn Olympic Games Berth|url=http://www.thesundevils.com/sports/c-track/recaps/062808aab.html|publisher=[[Arizona State Sun Devils]]|date=28 June 2008|accessdate=7 January 2013|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130216223418/http://www.thesundevils.com/sports/c-track/recaps/062808aab.html|archive-date=16 February 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gordon|first=Ed|title=Fountain's hot run of PBs takes her to a world leading 6667 \u2013 US Trials Heptathlon|url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/fountains-hot-run-of-pbs-takes-her-to-a-world|publisher=[[IAAF]]|date=29 June 2008|accessdate=7 January 2013}}</ref> Johnson was a member of the track and field team for the [[Arizona State Sun Devils]], where she wa coached and trained by [[Dan O'Brien]], gold medalist in the decathlon at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia]].<ref name=usatf>{{cite web|title=USATF \u2013 Jacquelyn Johnson|url=http://www.legacy.usatf.org/athletes/bios/TrackAndFieldArchive/2009/Johnson_Jacquelyn.asp|publisher=[[USA Track & Field]]|accessdate=7 January 2013}}</ref> In 2008, she won the [[Honda Sports Award]] as the nation's best female collegiate track and field athlete.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thesundevils.com/sports/2008/6/12/207819006.aspx|title=ASU's Jacquelyn Johnson Earns Honda Sports Award for Track & Field|website=Arizona State University Athletics|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collegiatewomensportsawards.com/archives/trackfield|title=Track & Field|website=CWSA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in [[Beijing]], Johnson competed as a member of the U.S. track and field team in the [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's heptathlon|women's heptathlon]], along with her fellow athletes [[Diana Pickler]] and [[Hyleas Fountain]]. Although she accomplished five events and reached into the higher position, Johnson, however, strained her left hamstring in the long jump, and was forced to withdraw from the competition because of the injury.<ref>{{cite news|last=Carifio|first=Edward|url=http://www.yumasun.com/news/pickler-43757-heptathlete-withdrew.html|title=Yuma native forced to drop out of Games|publisher=Yuma Sun|date=21 August 2008|accessdate=7 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Women's Heptathlon|url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/trackandfield/resultsandschedules/rsc=ATW700000/eventstandings.html|publisher=[[NBC Olympics]]|accessdate=7 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730235628/http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/trackandfield/resultsandschedules/rsc=ATW700000/eventstandings.html|archive-date=30 July 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nShe competed for [[Yuma Union High School]], where she won 14 Arizona state championships.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://legacy.usatf.org/athletes/bios/TrackAndFieldArchive/2009/Johnson_Jacquelyn.asp|title=Jacquelyn Johnson|website=legacy.usatf.org|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Personal bests==\n{|class=wikitable style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|- \n!Event\n!Best\n!Venue\n!Year\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[100 meter hurdles]]\n|13.88 s\n|[[Glendale, Arizona]], United States\n|May 9, 2001\n|\n|-\n|[[High jump]]\n|1.83 m \n|[[Tucson, Arizona]], United States\n|January 1, 2003\n|\n|-\n|[[Shot put]]\n|13.14 m \n|[[Des Moines, Iowa]], United States\n|April 22, 2009\n|\n|-\n|[[200 meters]]\n|24.44 s\n|[[San Francisco, California]], United States\n|June 9, 2006\n|\n|-\n|[[Long jump]]\n|6.12 m\n|[[Des Moines, Iowa]], United States\n|June 14, 2008\n|\n|-\n|[[Javelin throw]]\n|47.71 m\n|[[Eugene, Oregon]], United States\n|June 28, 2008\n|\n|-\n|[[800 meters]]\n|2:15.75\n|[[Des Moines, Iowa]], United States\n|JApril 23, 2009\n|\n|-style=\"background-color:#ccccff\"\n|[[Heptathlon]]\n|6,347 points\n|[[Eugene, Oregon]], United States\n|June 28, 2008\n|\n|}\n\n*<small>All information taken from IAAF profile.</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{iaaf name|id=184806|name=Jackie Johnson}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130406124852/http://www.thesundevils.com/sports/c-track/mtt/johnson_jacquelyn00.html Profile \u2013 Arizona State Sun Devils]\n*[http://usoc.org/Athletes/JO/Jacquelyn-Johnson.aspx Team USA Profile]\n*[http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/athletes/athlete=1271/bio/index.html NBC 2008 Olympics profile] {{dead link|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Footer USA Track & Field 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Honda Sports Award}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, Jackie}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American heptathletes]]\n[[Category:Olympic track and field athletes of the United States]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Arizona State Sun Devils women's track and field athletes]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from San Jose, California]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Tempe, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Track and field athletes from California]]\n\n\n{{US-heptathlon-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American heptathlete}}\n{{Infobox athlete\n| headercolor = lightblue\n| name           = Jackie Johnson\n| image          = \n| imagesize      = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = Jacquelyn Kate Johnson\n| nickname       = \n| nationality    = {{USA}}\n| residence      = [[Tempe, Arizona]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1984|9|8|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[San Jose, California]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = {{height|m=1.73|abbr=on}}\n| weight         = {{convert|62|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| website        = \n| country        = \n| sport          = [[Athletics (sport)|Athletics]]\n| event          = [[Heptathlon]]\n| collegeteam    = \n| club           =\n| team           = [[Arizona State Sun Devils]]<ref name=usatf/> \n| turnedpro      = \n| coach          = [[Dan O'Brien]]<ref name=usatf/>\n| retired        = \n| coaching       = \n| worlds         = \n| regionals      = \n| nationals      = \n| olympics       = \n| paralympics    = \n| highestranking = \n| pb             = '''Heptathlon''': 6,347 points (2008)\n| medaltemplates = \n}}\n\n'''Jacquelyn Kate \"Jackie\" Johnson''' (born September 8, 1984 in [[San Jose, California]]) is an American heptathlete.<ref>{{cite sports-reference|Jackie Johnson|https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/jo/jackie-johnson-1.html|7 January 2013}}</ref> She is a four-time NCAA outdoor champion (2004, 2006\u20132008), and a three-time NCAA indoor champion (2006\u20132008) while competing for [[Arizona State Sun Devils|Arizona State University]]. She also set a personal best of 6,347 points by placing second at the 2008 U.S. Olympic Trials in [[Eugene, Oregon]], which guaranteed her a qualifying place for the Olympics.<ref>{{cite news|title=Johnson Places Second in Heptathlon to Earn Olympic Games Berth|url=http://www.thesundevils.com/sports/c-track/recaps/062808aab.html|publisher=[[Arizona State Sun Devils]]|date=28 June 2008|accessdate=7 January 2013|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130216223418/http://www.thesundevils.com/sports/c-track/recaps/062808aab.html|archive-date=16 February 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gordon|first=Ed|title=Fountain's hot run of PBs takes her to a world leading 6667 \u2013 US Trials Heptathlon|url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/fountains-hot-run-of-pbs-takes-her-to-a-world|publisher=[[IAAF]]|date=29 June 2008|accessdate=7 January 2013}}</ref> Johnson was a member of the track and field team for the [[Arizona State Sun Devils]], where she wa coached and trained by [[Dan O'Brien]], gold medalist in the decathlon at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia]].<ref name=usatf>{{cite web|title=USATF \u2013 Jacquelyn Johnson|url=http://www.legacy.usatf.org/athletes/bios/TrackAndFieldArchive/2009/Johnson_Jacquelyn.asp|publisher=[[USA Track & Field]]|accessdate=7 January 2013}}</ref> In 2008, she won the [[Honda Sports Award]] as the nation's best female collegiate track and field athlete.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thesundevils.com/sports/2008/6/12/207819006.aspx|title=ASU's Jacquelyn Johnson Earns Honda Sports Award for Track & Field|website=Arizona State University Athletics|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collegiatewomensportsawards.com/archives/trackfield|title=Track & Field|website=CWSA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in [[Beijing]], Johnson competed as a member of the U.S. track and field team in the [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's heptathlon|women's heptathlon]], along with her fellow athletes [[Diana Pickler]] and [[Hyleas Fountain]]. Although she accomplished five events and reached into the higher position, Johnson, however, strained her left hamstring in the long jump, and was forced to withdraw from the competition because of the injury.<ref>{{cite news|last=Carifio|first=Edward|url=http://www.yumasun.com/news/pickler-43757-heptathlete-withdrew.html|title=Yuma native forced to drop out of Games|publisher=Yuma Sun|date=21 August 2008|accessdate=7 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Women's Heptathlon|url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/trackandfield/resultsandschedules/rsc=ATW700000/eventstandings.html|publisher=[[NBC Olympics]]|accessdate=7 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730235628/http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/trackandfield/resultsandschedules/rsc=ATW700000/eventstandings.html|archive-date=30 July 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nShe competed for [[Yuma Union High School]], where she won 14 Arizona state championships.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://legacy.usatf.org/athletes/bios/TrackAndFieldArchive/2009/Johnson_Jacquelyn.asp|title=Jacquelyn Johnson|website=legacy.usatf.org|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Personal bests==\n{|class=wikitable style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|- \n!Event\n!Best\n!Venue\n!Year\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[100 meter hurdles]]\n|13.88 s\n|[[Glendale, Arizona]], United States\n|May 9, 2001\n|\n|-\n|[[High jump]]\n|1.83 m \n|[[Tucson, Arizona]